  "prompt": "Why sound waves cannot be polarized?",
  "response": "Sound waves cannot be polarized because they are **longitudinal waves**, meaning the oscillations of the particles occur in the same direction as the wave's propagation. Polarization, on the other hand, is a phenomenon that applies specifically to **transverse waves**, where the oscillations occur perpendicular to the direction of wave propagation.\n\nFor example:\n- **Light waves** (electromagnetic waves) are transverse waves, and they can be polarized because their electric and magnetic fields oscillate perpendicular to the direction of travel. An example of polarization is using a polarizing filter to block certain orientations of light waves.\n- **Sound waves**, however, involve compressions and rarefactions of the medium (e.g., air), with the particles oscillating back and forth along the direction of wave travel. Since there is no perpendicular oscillation, sound waves cannot be polarized.\n\nIn summary, polarization requires a transverse wave, and sound waves are longitudinal, so they cannot be polarized.",
